## Write-Time Defaults — apply to every function without being asked

These are the cheapest possible prevention for the most expensive gap classes. They are
not suggestions; they are the default shape of every function you write.

- **Validate at the entry boundary (BOUNDARY-1).** Parse `req.body`, route params, and
  tool/CLI args with a Zod/Pydantic schema *at the handler*. Never access `body.foo` /
  `data["key"]` on untrusted input without a parse first. The boundary owns the contract;
  helpers trust it — never re-validate deep inside.
- **Auth first, fail closed (BOUNDARY-2).** `auth()` (or equivalent) is the **first line**
  of every protected handler, before any DB read. Any exception in the auth check
  *rejects* the request — never falls through to allow. `user?.id` in a route that requires
  auth is a lie: if auth passed, `user` is not optional.
- **Tenant/owner column in every write WHERE (BOUNDARY-4).** Every `UPDATE`/`DELETE` and
  every owner-scoped `SELECT` filters on the tenant/owner column, not just the PK. `LIMIT`
  on every user-facing read.
- **Soft-delete filter everywhere (BOUNDARY-3).** When a model gains `deleted_at`, add
  `deleted_at IS NULL` to *every* auth/read query against that table in the same change —
  especially the auth lookup. A soft-deleted user with a live session is an auth bypass.
- **Typed errors, no silent catch (FAIL-1).** Every `catch (e: unknown)` / `except`
  narrows before use and then re-throws, returns a typed error, or logs + returns a safe
  value. No bare `except Exception` / `catch` near IO that absorbs an unexpected type and
  runs a fallback. Generic message to the client, structured error to the logger — never
  leak table/column/constraint names.
- **`Promise.all` / `asyncio.gather` by default (PERF-2).** Independent awaits run in
  parallel; sequential only when the first feeds the second.
- **No blocking IO in the hot path (PERF-1).** No synchronous loopback, blocking
  `open`/`sleep`/`requests` in an `async` request path. One blocking call added to a
  per-request path is a latency cliff for *every* call.
- **No `any` (TS).** Use `unknown` and narrow with `instanceof` / `typeof` / Zod `.parse()`.
  Exhaustive `switch` on a union gets a `never` default (ties to SEAM-3).

### If this project has an LLM/agent that can write state (AGENT-*)

Skip this block for non-agentic projects.

- **Idempotency key on every write tool (AGENT-I).** Accept an optional `idempotency_key`
  (derive from an input hash if omitted), store with a unique constraint, return the
  existing record on conflict. LLM clients retry on *timeout*, not just network error — one
  logical action writes twice without this. See `scaffold/contract/idempotency.ts`.
- **Two-stage commit for destructive/consequential writes (AGENT-T).** No `confirmed=true`
  param ⇒ preview only, no state change. The model proposes; a deterministic layer commits.
- **Gate-exempt sets at module scope, not in the handler (AGENT-T).** A gate the request
  handler can reconfigure is not a gate.
- **Fixed category space (AGENT-A).** Enums, tool set, and permission scopes are fixed at
  build time. A value the persistence layer has never seen is rejected, not absorbed (ties
  to SEAM-3 — see the canonical-id guard in `scaffold/contract/canonical-ids.ts`).

